Pine, Jeffrey (Pinus jeffreyi Murray) is a tree of the family Pinaceae, native to north America. It takes its name from the botanist scotland John Jeffrey, active around the mid-NINETEENTH century.
FoglieLe leaves are needle-like, long about 25 cm, rigid, blue-green, gathered in groups of three and taken to the branches usually smooth.
FioriI male flowers are red, which becomes yellow at the time of the opening; the female flowers are red-purple on the separate clusters on the young branches at the beginning of the summer.
Distribution and habitatIl pine Jeffrey is widespread in the western United States, mainly on the slopes of the Sierra Nevada in California, but also Oregon's southwest and in northern Mexico (Baja California). It grows on slopes in the dry at high altitude: from 1500 to 2100 m in the northern part of its range, while in the southern part you can find from 1800 to 2900 m.
